80:Presumably, by ignorance of the absolute scale of the problem one ought to mean a state of knowledge that is not changed by a small change in that absolute scale; just as ignorance of one's location is a state of knowledge that is not changed by a small change in that location. One may, therefore, view "ignorance" as an invariance property; the probability density that is invariant under the group of scale changes ($\theta \to \theta^\prime = a\theta$) satisfies the functional equation $f(\theta) = af(a\theta)$; i.e., it is $f(\theta|I) = (1/\theta)$.
