99:This example shows how the inference (9) can answer, successfully, a more modest question than the direct inversion (3) tried to answer, unsuccessfully. Our conclusions are numerically stable, and the way in which the accuracy of those conclusions depends on the amount of data is now exhibited explicitly in (12).
100:Note, however, that in answering a more modest question, inference is not giving us any less information than inversion; for when a reliable inversion is possible, the likelihood factor $p(D|\theta,I)$ in (6) develops a single sharp peak and inference will reduce to inversion. An unstable inversion, with the superficial appearance of giving more information, is actually giving false/unreliable information without warning us of that fact. Inference gives us those conclusions that are actually justified by the prior information and data, and it tells us, by the probable error $\sigma$, how reliable our estimates are. It may also take into account prior information that inversion ignores.
