   104	
   105	In Laplace's problems, the final algorithm usually turned out to be weighted least squares. Unfortunately, then as now there was a tendency to confuse the algorithm with the method. In the nineteenth Century, losing sight of Laplace's rationale, "Least Squares" came to be considered a principle in its own right, to be applied indiscriminately in all problems whether or not it could be justified by the principles of probability theory. To avoid repeating past mistakes, it is important that in each new problem we re-examine the probabilistic basis for our algorithm.
   106	
   107	In our present problem, the experiment consists of $K$ repetitions of the measurement of $n$; denote the data obtained by $D = \{n_1, n_2, \dots, n_K\}$, and any additional prior information (which might be the result of previous experiments or a theoretical analysis) by $I$ and let $T$ stand for the statement: "$\theta$ is in the interval $(\theta, \theta+d\theta)$". The evidence $I$ contains some information about $\theta$, described by a probability $p(T|I)$. From the product rule of probability theory:
   108	
   109	$$
   110	p(T,D|I) = p(T|D,I)p(D|I) = p(D|T,I)p(T|I)
   111	$$
   112	we have, if $p(D|I) > 0$ (i.e., the data set is a possible one),
   113	
   114	$$p(T|D,I) = p(T|I) \frac{p(D|T,I)}{p(D|I)} \tag{5}$$
   115	
   116	Then, indicating a probability density $f(\theta|X)$ of $\theta$ conditional on any information $X$ according to $p(T|X) = f(\theta|X)d\theta$, the final probability distribution for $\theta$, given the prior information and the data, will have the form
   117	
   118	$$f(\theta|D,I) = A f(\theta|I) p(D|\theta,I) \tag{6}$$
   119	
   120	where $A$ is a normalizing constant, independent of $\theta$. The evidence contained in the experimental data $D$ thus resides entirely in the $\theta$ dependence of the factor $p(D|\theta,I)$; all other details of the data are irrelevant for the estimation of $\theta$. Usually, $I$ will be relevant to the probability of obtaining the data $D$ only through its relevance to the value of $\theta$, in which case it is superfluous in this factor: $p(D|\theta,I) = p(D|\theta)$.
